ce:section.ce:para:
The developed PGr/CdTe QDs/Fe3O4@SiO2/MIP probe was applied to detect cefoperazone in milk. In some milk samples, residual levels of cefoperazone were found between non-detectable and 0.52 μg L−1. To evaluate the accuracy of the developed nano-optosensor, it was applied to detect various concentrations of cefoperazone spiked in milk samples. The accuracy of the system was evaluated in terms of relative recovery (%), which was calculated from the following equation: Relative recovery (%) = (CF − CS/CA) × 100, where CF is the total cefoperazone found in a spiked sample, CS is the cefoperazone in a real sample and CA is the standard cefoperazone spiked in a milk sample. Recoveries were within the range of 85.3 to 98.3% with a RSDs < 6% (Table 1
                        ), which are acceptable. The performance of the nano-optosensor was compared with an HPLC method. Standard cefoperazone was spiked in samples pre-treated as described in Section 2.7. Since the sensitivity of the HPLC was lower than the sensitivity of the proposed nano-optosensor, the cefoperazone extracted from milk was diluted before analysis with the optosensor but remained undiluted for HPLC analysis. The plot of cefoperazone detected in milk samples showed a good agreement between the developed nano-optosensor and the HPLC. R2 was 0.9921 (Fig. 4
                        A). HPLC chromatograms of milk samples spiked with cefoperazone at various level are shown in Fig. 4B. The results indicated that the developed nano-optosensor accurately determined cefoperazone in the milk.
